{"mcp_tool":"mcd_query","arguments":{"sql":"with variant as (select variant_id, curb_mass_kg, drag_coefficient, frontal_area_m2, (cast(drag_coefficient as real) * cast(frontal_area_m2 as real)) as baseline_cda_m2, ((cast(drag_coefficient as real) + 0.020) * cast(frontal_area_m2 as real)) as new_cda_m2, (((cast(drag_coefficient as real) + 0.020) * cast(frontal_area_m2 as real)) - (cast(drag_coefficient as real) * cast(frontal_area_m2 as real))) as delta_cda_m2 from vehicle_variant_configuration_specs where lower(variant_id)=lower('OAM-V0320')) select * from variant"}}
{"answer":"For variant_id OAM-V0320, curb_mass_kg is unchanged, but the aerodynamic road-load term still increases because the dossier’s aero basis depends on CdA, not mass. Using the variant row fields drag_coefficient and frontal_area_m2: baseline drag_coefficient = 0.31, frontal_area_m2 = 2.95, so baseline CdA = 0.9145 m2; with a +0.020 Cd increase, new drag_coefficient = 0.33 and new CdA = 0.9735 m2; absolute CdA change = +0.0590 m2. That is why range would drop even though curb_mass_kg stays at 2286 kg: mass mainly affects inertial/rolling-related load, while aerodynamic road load rises with CdA, so at the same speed the vehicle must overcome more drag force and consume more energy per distance. In short: same curb_mass_kg, higher drag_coefficient -> higher CdA (0.9145 to 0.9735 m2) -> higher aerodynamic road load -> lower range."}

